   at System.Net.Browser.AsyncHelper.&lt;&gt;c__DisplayClass1.&lt;BeginOnUI&gt;b__0(Object sendState)}  System.Exception {System.ArgumentException}
</code></pre>

<p>Shown below is the code snippet.</p>

<pre><code>using (HttpClient client = new HttpClient(handler) { MaxResponseContentBufferSize = Int32.MaxValue })
{
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Authorization", "Bearer " + accessToken);

    try
    {
        var fileResponse = await client.GetAsync(requestUrl, HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);                    

        if (fileResponse != null &amp;&amp; fileResponse.StatusCode == System.Net.HttpStatusCode.OK)
            return await fileResponse.Content.ReadAsByteArrayAsync();
        else return null;
    }
    catch(Exception e)
    {
        System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine("Error in getAsync, " + e.StackTrace);                    
        return null;
    }

}
</code></pre>

<p>Note that this only happens for files with Korean (non-English) filenames and corrupted files. For image files and non-corrupted files, I was able to download successfully. (Example of corrupted file is a word or ppt file that shows an error msg when opened).</p>
