<pre><code>Function UploadToBox(ByVal attachedFilename As String, ByVal stream As System.IO.Stream) As Boolean

    Dim clientID As String
    Dim clientSecret As String
    Dim oldRefreshToken As String
    Dim newToken As BoxApi.V2.Authentication.OAuth2.OAuthToken

    clientID = "your client id"
    clientSecret = "you client secret"

    Dim tokenProvider As New TokenProvider(clientID, clientSecret)

    '''' Reading Refresh token from the file
    Dim streamReader As StreamReader
    streamReader = System.IO.File.OpenText(Server.MapPath("~\\Box\\BoxApiRefreshToken.txt"))
    oldRefreshToken = streamReader.ReadToEnd()
    streamReader.Close()

    newToken = tokenProvider.RefreshAccessToken(oldRefreshToken)
    Dim boxManager As New BoxManager(newToken.AccessToken)

    '''' Writing the new Refresh token to the file
    Dim streamWriter As New StreamWriter(Server.MapPath("~\\Box\\BoxApiRefreshToken.txt"))
    streamWriter.Write(newToken.RefreshToken)
    streamWriter.Close()

    Dim rootFolder As Folder

    rootFolder = boxManager.GetFolder(Folder.Root)

    boxManager.CreateFile(rootFolder, attachedFilename, ConvertStreamToByteArray(stream))

    Return True

End Function 
</code></pre>

<p>mentioned here
<a href="http://www.codeproject.com/Tips/769414/Uploading-files-using-Box-API" rel="nofollow">http://www.codeproject.com/Tips/769414/Uploading-files-using-Box-API</a></p>

<p>The UploadToBox method is in a loop and called for every file we need to upload. However, after few uploads, we are getting the error </p>

<p><strong>The underlying connection was closed: A connection that was expected to be kept alive was closed by the server.</strong></p>

<p>Intuitively it appears that the connection to box is getting closed. But from the code above, we dont know which part is trying to create the connection, and if its closed then create a new one. Its fairly easy with c# SqlConnection to check if connection is open or closed.</p>

<p>Please suggest your thoughts.</p>
"},{"tags":["box-api"],"owner":{"reputation":53,"user_id":3904874,"user_type":"registered","profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2663e8f1cd8af4d6a497da6fdfd25c53?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","display_name":"ZinaliErik","link":"https://stackoverflow.com/users/3904874/zinalierik"},"is_answered":true,"view_count":252,"accepted_answer_id":28083367,"answer_count":1,"score":0,"last_activity_date":1421911851,"creation_date":1421816940,"last_edit_date":1495540262,"question_id":28060036,"link":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28060036/getting-rename-event-from-box-webhook-also-are-events-preferred-to-webhook-in-b","title":"Getting rename event from Box webhook, also are events preferred to webhook in Box?","body":"<p>I'm trying to use webhooks to get notifications for changes in a user's Box account.  One thing I don't see is an option to get a webhook notification when an item is renamed. Is it possible to get a notification for rename?  I see that RENAME is available via the event API, is it preferable to use the event API?  I saw another stackoverflow question asking about webhook vs event (<a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/20320795/box-webhooks-deprecated-in-favor-of-long-polling">Box webhooks deprecated in favor of long polling?</a>) and the answer said webhooks are still valid, but didn't really comment on webhook vs event.</p>

<p>I'd prefer webhooks since they are a close fit to how I get changes for Dropbox accounts but it appears from the docs that event has more information/options. Also, it seems it's possible to miss a Box webhook notification which could create an inconsistent state between Box the model in my application.</p>

<p>Which to choose?</p>

<p>Many thanks!</p>
"},{"tags":["javascript","oauth","box-api","box","boxapiv2"],"owner":{"reputation":382,"user_id":1241610,"user_type":"registered","profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d2bd9c25151d6c861d9762f616be5ec1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","display_name":"Joels Elf","link":"https://stackoverflow.com/users/1241610/joels-elf"},"is_answered":false,"view_count":478,"answer_count":1,"score":0,"last_activity_date":1421318421,"creation_date":1421260657,"last_edit_date":1421260997,"question_id":27950098,"link":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/27950098/how-to-get-box-access-token-from-a-webpage-html-or-javascript","title":"How to get Box access token from a webpage html or javascript?","body":"<p>Hi I'm trying to login a user to Box.com from a webpage. I accomplished the first part with a simple HTML form submit:</p>

<pre><code>&lt;form action="https://www.box.com/api/oauth2/authorize" type="POST" enctype="application/x-www-form-urlencoded"&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="response_type" value="code"&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="client_id" value="[REMOVED]"&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="state" value="vexhax97td8xf_SomeTemporaryValueForTesting"&gt;
    &lt;input type="submit"&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
</code></pre>

<p>This works fine, and I get the authorization code from the query parameters using javascript. I then try the same thing to get the access code (the auth-code is set by javascript on page load):</p>

<pre><code>&lt;form action="https://app.box.com/api/oauth2/token" type="POST" enctype="application/x-www-form-urlencoded"&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="grant_type" value="authorization_code"&gt;
    &lt;input id="auth-code" type="text" name="code" value=""&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="client_id" value="[REMOVED]"&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="client_secret" value="[REMOVED]"&gt;
    &lt;input type="submit"&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
</code></pre>

<p>But I get an "Invalid grant_type parameter or parameter missing" error. Plus this wouldn't be a good user experience to show the response json anyway. I've tried it without the <code>enctype="application/x-www-form-urlencoded"</code> and get the same error.</p>

<p>The Box tutorial does it with curl which obviously isn't an option on a webpage. How do I get the access token without hitting the "Invalid..." error and is there a way to do this via javascript behind the scenes?</p>
