"},{"tags":["box-api"],"owner":{"reputation":3,"user_id":2840405,"user_type":"registered","profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0a0b7c9cfffc0f80544ab840b36e2353?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","display_name":"Ben Gilbert","link":"https://stackoverflow.com/users/2840405/ben-gilbert"},"is_answered":true,"view_count":191,"accepted_answer_id":20156245,"answer_count":1,"score":0,"last_activity_date":1385162019,"creation_date":1385157167,"last_edit_date":1385157277,"question_id":20155169,"link":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/20155169/box-java-sdk-throws-nullpointerexception-when-trying-to-refresh-a-revoked-token","title":"Box Java SDK throws NullPointerException when trying to refresh a revoked token","body":"<p>We're using the latest version of the Box Java SDK to finish our port from the Box v1 API to the Box v2 API. Overall the SDK is great, and a huge time-saver over what we had to do with V1.</p>

<p>However, I've encountered a problem in testing that I believe should be fixed. If you try to call the BoxOAuthManager.refreshOAuth method using a token that has been revoked on the Box side, the method throws a NullPointerException.  Here's a code sample (assumes you have valid values for token/credentials, and a BoxClient instance in CLIENT):</p>

<pre><code>BoxOAuthRequestObject refreshRequest = 
    BoxOAuthRequestObject.refreshOAuthRequestObject(REFRESH_TOKEN, CLIENT_ID, CLIENT_SECRET);

BoxOAuthToken boxToken = CLIENT.getOAuthManager().refreshOAuth(refreshRequest);
</code></pre>

<p>I would expect this to throw an AuthFatalFailureException if the refresh token is invalid, but instead it throws a NullPointerException. So as a workaround we are making sure to catch the NullPointerException in our code and respond appropriately.</p>

<p>The null pointer appears to be on line 36 of ErrorResponseParser.java.</p>
