"},{"tags":["objective-c","ios","box-api"],"owner":{"reputation":149,"user_id":1009687,"user_type":"registered","accept_rate":86,"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1e5c0ac5b504c44f7f4827fb7cc75f14?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","display_name":"CodeBreaker","link":"https://stackoverflow.com/users/1009687/codebreaker"},"is_answered":true,"view_count":183,"accepted_answer_id":14039667,"answer_count":1,"score":0,"last_activity_date":1356519728,"creation_date":1356331875,"last_edit_date":1356333339,"question_id":14018085,"link":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14018085/sign-in-as-a-different-box-user","title":"Sign in as a different Box user","body":"<p>I am trying to integrate my iPad app with Box. I am having an issue with the Box API where files in the account of one user are returned for some other user. Here are the steps to reproduce this issue:</p>

<ol>
<li>Make the authorization calls and get the access token as mentioned in <a href="http://developers.box.com/oauth/" rel="nofollow">this</a> guide. For login, I am opening the Box login page in Safari. I have the specified a custom url scheme for the redirect url, which opens up my app after the user logs in.</li>
<li>Once you get the access token, make a call to list the contents of the root folder. This succeeds.</li>
<li>Delete the app from  the iPad and rebuild it.</li>
<li>Again go to the login process (as in step 1), but this time use a different Box account to login. You get a new access code and OAuth token this time.</li>
<li>If you make the call to list the files using the new token, you will get the response from the earlier account. Ideally it should return the files for the currently authorized user.</li>
</ol>

<p>Does Box use just OAuth to return response or does it use cookies as well? Because after authentication and receiving the access token, I also see a cookie from Box (verified using <code>[[NSHTTPCookieStorage sharedStorage] cookies]</code>).</p>

<p>I have tried repeating the above process by deleting all Box cookies before starting the authentication flow. Also, I am not saving the OAuth token on disk and retrieving it. I am not saving/caching the response in any way.</p>

<p>One more thing that I have noticed is that there can be two Box users logged in at once in Safari. Also, if I make the authentication request, get the access token and again make the authentication request, it shows the login page again (instead of showing the allow/deny access page). Is this intentional?</p>

<p><em>I am using the Box v2 API and iOS 5/6</em></p>
"},{"tags":["box-api"],"owner":{"reputation":11,"user_id":1806018,"user_type":"registered","profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4efe01985b281a1049f61a610b9a2583?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","display_name":"DGoomany","link":"https://stackoverflow.com/users/1806018/dgoomany"},"is_answered":true,"view_count":380,"answer_count":1,"score":0,"last_activity_date":1356003670,"creation_date":1356001883,"question_id":13970897,"link":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13970897/upload-a-file-to-my-own-box-net-account-from-javascript-or-php","title":"Upload a file to my own box.net account from Javascript or PHP.","body":"<p>I have a box.net account and I want to be able to upload a file to my own account via a Javascript script I'm writing (which is collating data as JSON). I also wouldn't mind doing this via PHP by AJAXing the data to a PHP script. </p>

